"1077","soscisubmission7","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","Theory of Mind, implicit Theory of Mind, eye-tracking","Implicit Theory of Mind can be measured through anticipatory looking patterns measured through eye-tracking.","Crucially, in the replication only the ""FB1"" condition was replicated, which is prone to alternative explanations, while the ""FB2"" condition, which exlcudes alternative explanations showed effects in the opposite direction to the original study.","Kulke, Louisa","45016.0",NA,NA,"0.469","0.124","20.0","52.0","Southgate, V., Senju, A., & Csibra, G. (2007). Action anticipation through attribution of false belief by 2-year-olds. Psychological science, 18(7), 587-592.","Kulke, L., von Duhn, B., Schneider, D., & Rakoczy, H. (2018). Is implicit theory of mind a real and robust phenomenon? Results from a systematic replication study. Psychological science, 29(6), 888-900.",NA,NA,"0.22","etasq","0.25","d",NA,NA,NA,NA,"http:// journals.sagepub.com/doi/suppl/10.1177/0956797617747090",NA,"2.0","sosci_KPsychSci","1.0","0.0","0.0",NA,NA,NA,NA,"Kulke, L., von Duhn, B., Schneider, D., & Rakoczy, H. (2018). Is implicit theory of mind a real and robust phenomenon? Results from a systematic replication study. Psychological science, 29(6), 888-900., p.893",NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate","https://osf.io/dxb5n/","2.0","2.0","1.0","2.0","1.0","4.0","3.0","1.0","3.0","3.0","The replication tested adults instead of the toddlers tested in the original study, as the original and later studies suggest that the effect is consistent across the life span. The replication included four different paradigms which were tested within participants, while the original only included one paradigm. The replication computed the same eye movement measures but used the Differential Looking Score (DLS) as suggested in a later study by the original authors (Senju et al., 2009); therefore, the used statistics differ. The replication tested German participants, instead of British participants. The authors of the original study provided the original stimuli for the replication. One author of a different original Theory of Mind paradigm is also a co-author on the replication. 
 Crucially, in the replication only the ""FB1"" condition was replicated, which is prone to alternative explanations, while the ""FB2"" condition, which exlcudes alternative explanations showed effects in the opposite direction to the original study.",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Psychological Science",NA,NA,NA,NA
