"1090","soscisubmission14c","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","utilitarianism, alcohol, CNI Model, trolley dilemma, moral judgmenet","drunk utilitarian","We revisited the ""drunk utilitarian"" phenomena which was indicated by Duke and Begue in 2015. Our study replicated the results of Francis et al., 2019, and Arutyunova et al., 2017 but we proposed more strict methodolody and more measures to study utilitarianism. We show that there is no such phenomena as ""drunk utilitarian"", people are not more utilitarian when they are under the influence of the alcohol.","Pypno Katarzyna; Paruzel-Czachura Mariola","45022.0",NA,NA,"0.29","0.130384","60.0","329.0","Duke, A. A., & Bègue, L. (2015). The drunk utilitarian: Blood alcohol concentration predicts utilitarian responses in moral dilemmas. Cognition, 134, 121–127. https://doi.org/10.1016/j. cognition.2014.09.006 Study 1","Paruzel-Czachura, M., Pypno, K., Everett, J.A., Białek, M.J., & Gawronski, B. (2023). The Drunk Utilitarian Revisited: Does Alcohol Really Increase Utilitarianism in Moral Judgment? Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin, 49, 20–31. https://doi.org/10.1177/01461672211052120",NA,NA,"0.29","r","0.017","etasq",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/9vn5z/",NA,"2.0","sosci_11c","1.0","0.0","1.0",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate","https://osf.io/avf49","2.0","2.0","2.0","3.0","3.0","4.0","3.0","2.0","3.0","3.0",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Cognition",NA,NA,NA,NA
