"1110","soscisubmission34","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","expressive responding, political psychology ","Trump voters/Republicans select the incorrect inauguration crowd photo more often than non-Trump voters/non-Republicans",NA,"Ross, Robert M.","45027.0","Test statistics were not reported thoroughly in the oringal study. However, the p-value combined with the figure makes it clear what hypothesis was being tested and that the replication was successful.",NA,NA,NA,"651.0","954.0","Schaffner, B. F., & Luks, S. (2018). Misinformation or expressive responding? What an inauguration crowd can tell us about the source of political misinformation in surveys. Public Opinion Quarterly, 82(1), 135–147. https://doi.org/10.1093/poq/nfx042","Ross, R. M., & Levy, N. (2023). Expressive Responding in Support of Donald Trump: An Extended Replication of Schaffner and Luks (2018). Collabra: Psychology, 9(1). https://doi.org/10.1525/collabra.68054",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/dhr36/",NA,"2.0","sosci_14","1.0","1.0","1.0",NA,NA,"chi_squ(?,?) = ?, p < .01","chi-squ(1, N = 953) = 5.365, p = .021","Original study: Schaffner and Luks (2018) page 139.
 Replication study: Ross and Levy (2023) page 4.",NA,NA,NA,"success","https://osf.io/dhr36/registrations","1.0","2.0","1.0","2.0","1.0","2.0","2.0","2.0","1.0","1.0","The original study examined whether Trump voters selected the incorrect photo more often than Clinton voters and non-voters.
 
 The replication study examined whether Republicans selected the incorrect photo more often than Democrats (participants were forced to indicate which of the two parties that they identified with more strongly, so there was no third category unlike the original study).",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Public Opinion Quarterly","OS n.s.","NA - OS n.s.",NA,NA
