"1165","soscisubmission18","1.0",NA,"individual submissions","binge-watching; self-determination theory; media psychology; well-being","binge-goal conflict",NA,"Tobias Dienlin","45029.0",NA,NA,"0.65","0.47","499.0","668.0","Granow, V. C., Reinecke, L., & Ziegele, M. (2018). Binge-Watching and Psychological Well-Being: Media Use Between Lack of Control and Perceived Autonomy. Communication Research Reports, 35(5), 392–401. https://doi.org/10.1080/08824096.2018.1525347","Erdmann, E., & Dienlin, T. (2022). Binge-watching, self-determination, and well-being: A partially successful direct replication and extension of Granow et al. (2018). Journal of Media Psychology, 1864-1105/a000334. https://doi.org/10.1027/1864-1105/a000334",NA,NA,"0.65","beta","0.47","beta",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"2.0",NA,"2.0","2.0","2.0",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"success",NA,"2.0","2.0","4.0","2.0","1.0","1.0","2.0","1.0","1.0","1.0","One item was changed in wording (""Based on feedback from the pretest, minor linguistic adjustments were made (e.g., “. . . I manage to distance myself from my (work) tasks” instead of “. . . dis- tance myself from work”) to ensure that non-working individuals also feel addressed.) The SEM that we fitted did not exactly represent the one in original study. In the original study several items were deleted to achieve good model fit. However, this procedure was not outlined in the paper, and we could not get the exact model from the original authors. In the original study, participants were collected via the sosci panel and additionally via Facebook. In the replication, participants were collected via Facebook.",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Communication Research Reports",NA,NA,NA,NA
