"1177","soscisubmission38","1.0","CD","Individual submissions","implicit attitudes, evaluative conditioning, awareness","Evaluative conditioning in the absence of awareness of stimulus pairings","The replication publication reports the effect size observed in the original publication, which was recalculated from the original study's t and df by another author of Moran et al. In the process of completing this form, I recalculated the original effect size and found a discrepency in Moran et al. (i.e., Moran's report of Olson & Fazio's effect size). I will now pursue a correction of this in Moran et al. with the first author.","Hussey, Ian","45069.0",NA,NA,NA,"0.05989229","50.0","1340.0","Olson, M. A., & Fazio, R. H. (2001). Implicit attitude formation through classical conditioning. Psychological Science, 12(5), 413-417, Study 2","Moran, T., Hughes, S., Hussey, I., Vadillo, M. A., Olson, M. A., Aust, F., ... & De Houwer, J. (2021). Incidental attitude formation via the surveillance task: A preregistered replication of the Olson and Fazio (2001) study. Psychological Science, 32(1), 120-131.",NA,NA,"0.277","dz","0.12","Hedges'g",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/hs32y/",NA,"2.0","sosci_16","1.0","0.0","0.0",NA,NA,"t(48) = 1.92, p = .03","Hedges’ g = 0.12, 95% CI [0.05, 0.20], z = 3.17, p = .002","Original result: Page 416, quote is ""and the explicit (paper-and-pencil) measure, t(48) = 1.92, p = .03"". Note that the original study also included an implicit measure whose results were also reported but not inlcuded here, as the replication study only included the self report measure. Also note that statcheck determines that this t and df recomputes a different p value to that reported in the text (i.e., p = .06). This discrepency was not noted in the published replication article. 
 
 Replication study: Page 7, under heading ""primary analysis"": ""The meta-analysis based on the original Olson and Fazio (2001) awareness criterion (n = 1,340, 9.2% excluded) showed that, on average, the surveillance task led to a small but significant evaluativeconditioning effect (Hedges’s g = 0.12, 95% CI = [0.05, 0.20], z = 3.17, p = .002) in the expected direction.""",NA,NA,NA,"inconclusive","https://osf.io/3hjpf","2.0","3.0","3.0","3.0","1.0","3.0","1.0","1.0","1.0","3.0","Procedure different in unknown ways and some known ways. Although the original authors were involved in the design of the replication study, they declined to share the specifics of the original study. This introduced unknown differences, such as specific format of the surveillance task (the experimental manipulation) and the evaluation task (the outcome). These were not noted in the replication publication. 
 
 They instead provided a design for what they considered to be the most likely to replicate what they considered to be the same descriptive effect. We're aware that one known difference was the addition of the Filler Task. This deviation was noted in the replication publication.","0.01763933","7.4148E-4",-0.0142424,0.50614762,0.0063618,0.1130805,0,1,1,"Psychological Science","OS n.s.","signal - OS n.s.",0.13917106,1.90525589
"1178","soscisubmission39","1.0","CD","Individual submissions","Affect Misattribution Procedure, implicit measures, Implicit Association Test, bias awareness, implicit social cognition","Effects in the Affect Misattribution Procedure are moderated by awareness of influence of the prime stimulus on evaluations of the target stimulus",NA,"Cummins, Jamie","45069.0",NA,NA,NA,NA,"72.0","295.0","Payne BK, Brown-Iannuzzi J, Burkley M, Arbuckle NL, Cooley E, Cameron CD, Lundberg KB. Intention invention and the affect misattribution procedure: reply to Bar-Anan and Nosek (2012). Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin, 39(3), 375-86. 10.1177/0146167212475225, Study 3.","Hughes, S., Cummins, J., & Hussey, I. (2022). Effects on the Affect Misattribution Procedure are strongly moderated by influence awareness. Behavior Research Methods, 1-29. https://doi.org/10.3758/s13428-022-01879-4, Experiment 1",NA,NA,NA,NA,"0.96","d",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/j65gm/",NA,"2.0","sosci_17","0.0","0.0","1.0",NA,NA,"F(2, 134) = 0.60, p = .55 (two-tailed)","t(294) = 9.36, p < .001 (two-tailed), d = 0.96","Replication: Hughes, S., Cummins, J., & Hussey, I. (2022). Effects on the Affect Misattribution Procedure are strongly moderated by influence awareness. Behavior Research Methods: page 7 (hypothesis testing of Experiment 1 section). 
 
 Original: Payne BK, Brown-Iannuzzi J, Burkley M, Arbuckle NL, Cooley E, Cameron CD, Lundberg KB. Intention invention and the affect misattribution procedure: reply to Bar-Anan and Nosek (2012). Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin, 39(3): Page 383.",NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate","https://osf.io/2vt7y","2.0","2.0","1.0","2.0","3.0","3.0","2.0","2.0","1.0","2.0","The replication used a within-subjects design, whereas the original used a between-subjects design. The replication used an AMP consisting of positive and negative primes, whereas the original also included neutral primes (this was common in the field at the time but has been phased out of practice in recent years; our AMP represented the contemporary version of the task). 
 Our manipulation was within-subjects as mentioned already: participants completed both a skip-AMP and a standard AMP, whereas in the original participants complete either the skip-AMP or the standard AMP. 
 The original study modelled the difference between prime types within its analysis (i.e., an ANOVA with ""prime type"" as one of the IVs); our analysis simply computed difference scores rather than model this. Because of this, our analysis was instead a t-test comparing the skip- vs. standard-AMPs.
 Our instructions differed very slightly due to this change in design (since participants had already completed one of the AMPs they received shortened instructions for the second).
 Our study took place online; the original took place in person.
 Participants were remunerated via course credit in the original; they were remunerated financially in the replication.
 Our populations were both US citizens; however, the participants in the original were exclusively students whereas ours were not.",NA,"0.00224678",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"OS n.s.","NA - OS n.s.",NA,NA
