"1223","OpenMKT11","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","Moral values, Fairness, Luxury consumption. Consumption resources, Brand attitude","Unearned luxury consumption will lead to lower brand attitude than earned luxury consumption when consumers' fairness concerns are salient, but less so when fairness concerns are not salient.",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45158.0",NA,NA,"0.1276427","0.04290029","164.0","401.0","Lee, S., Baumgartner, H., & Winterich, K. P. (2018). Did they earn it? Observing unearned luxury consumption decreases brand attitude when observers value fairness. Journal of Consumer Psychology, 28(3), 412-436. Study 4","O’Donnell, M., Dev, A. S., Antonoplis, S., Baum, S. M., Benedetti, A. H., Brown, N. D., … & Nelson, L. D. (2021). Empirical audit and review and an assessment of evidentiary value in research on the psychological consequences of scarcity. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 118(44).",NA,NA,"0.1276427","r","0.04290029","r",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/a2e96/",NA,"2.0","openMKT11",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Consumer Psychology",NA,NA,NA,NA
"1224","OpenMKT12","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","financial constraints, discretionary spending, experiences and material goods, longevity, myopia","The consideration of financial constraints shifts consumers’ preferences toward material goods rather than experiences. (I.e. Inducing financial scarcity will lead individuals to prefer purchasing material goods over experiences.",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45158.0",NA,NA,"0.1613215","0.1355482","377.0","688.0","S. M. Tully, H. E. Hershfield, T. Meyvis, Seeking lasting enjoyment with limited money: Financial constraints increase preference for material goods over experiences. J. Consum. Res. 42, 59–75 Study 5","O’Donnell, M., Dev, A. S., Antonoplis, S., Baum, S. M., Benedetti, A. H., Brown, N. D., … & Nelson, L. D. (2021). Empirical audit and review and an assessment of evidentiary value in research on the psychological consequences of scarcity. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 118(44).",NA,NA,"0.1613215","r","0.1355482","r",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/a2e96/",NA,"2.0","openMKT12",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"success",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Consumer Research",NA,NA,NA,NA
"1225","OpenMKT13","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","time, money, scarcity, time-money tradeoffs, wage rates, procedural invariance","By manipulating the timing of an activity, the Time-Elicit (TEL) procedure of stating the maximum amount of hours required for a task should be more sensitive to a change in time scarcity, because time of money required for a task). Analogously, the TEL procedure should be more sensitive to a change in the timing of the activity. That is, distant activitiesscarcity receives a higher weight in TEL vs. Money-Elicit (MEL) procedure - stating the minimum amount should yield lower wage rates, particularly in the TEL (vs. MEL) procedure, which should diminish the wage rate asymmetry",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45158.0",NA,NA,"0.2164277","0.01732414","179.0","467.0","Monga, A., May, F., & Bagchi, R. (2017). Eliciting time versus money: time scarcity underlies asymmetric wage rates. Journal of consumer research, 44(4), 833-852. Study 4","O’Donnell, M., Dev, A. S., Antonoplis, S., Baum, S. M., Benedetti, A. H., Brown, N. D., … & Nelson, L. D. (2021). Empirical audit and review and an assessment of evidentiary value in research on the psychological consequences of scarcity. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 118(44).",NA,NA,"0.2164277","r","0.01732414","r",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/a2e96/",NA,"2.0","openMKT13",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Consumer Research",NA,NA,NA,NA
"1226","OpenMKT14","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","resource scarcity, competitive orientation, welfare advancement, selfish, generous","When scarcity is salient, pro-self individuals will engage in even more selfish behavior compared to prosocial individuals. The difference between proself individual’s behavior and prosocial individual’s behavior is attenuated when scarcity is not salient.",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45158.0",NA,NA,"0.1678662","0.00790159","157.0","414.0","Roux, C., Goldsmith, K., & Bonezzi, A. (2015). On the psychology of scarcity: When reminders of resource scarcity promote selfish (and generous) behavior. Journal of consumer research, 42(4), 615-631. Study 4","O’Donnell, M., Dev, A. S., Antonoplis, S., Baum, S. M., Benedetti, A. H., Brown, N. D., … & Nelson, L. D. (2021). Empirical audit and review and an assessment of evidentiary value in research on the psychological consequences of scarcity. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 118(44).",NA,NA,"0.1678662","r","0.00790159","r",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/a2e96/",NA,"2.0","openMKT14",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Consumer Research",NA,NA,NA,NA
"1227","OpenMKT15","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","creativity, innovativeness, product use, scarcity, abundance, resource constraints","Participants who encounter scarcity salience in a prior unrelated context would be more likely to use the provided products in novel but appropriate ways to solve the given task.",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45158.0",NA,NA,"0.2545049","0.09189366","88.0","225.0","Mehta, R., & Zhu, M. (2016). Creating when you have less: The impact of resource scarcity on product use creativity. Journal of Consumer Research, 42(5), 767-782. Study 2","O’Donnell, M., Dev, A. S., Antonoplis, S., Baum, S. M., Benedetti, A. H., Brown, N. D., … & Nelson, L. D. (2021). Empirical audit and review and an assessment of evidentiary value in research on the psychological consequences of scarcity. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 118(44).",NA,NA,"0.2545049","r","0.09189366","r",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/a2e96/",NA,"2.0","openMKT15",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Consumer Research",NA,NA,NA,NA
"1228","OpenMKT16","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","Advertising, Aggression, Consumer promotions, Scarcity, Violence","This study predicts that there will be higher preferences for violent experiences after exposure to the limited-quantity scarcity promotion (vs. control) among participants who did not reduce the competitive threat via the affiliation task (perceived competitive threat: high). This study also predicts an attenuation of the scarcity-aggression link among participants who did reduce the competitive threat via the affiliation task (perceived competitive threat: low).",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45158.0",NA,NA,"0.157341","0.003603726","160.0","389.0","Kristofferson, K., McFerran, B., Morales, A. C., & Dahl, D. W. (2017). The dark side of scarcity promotions: how exposure to limited-quantity promotions can induce aggression. Journal of Consumer Research, 43(5), 683-706. Study 5","O’Donnell, M., Dev, A. S., Antonoplis, S., Baum, S. M., Benedetti, A. H., Brown, N. D., … & Nelson, L. D. (2021). Empirical audit and review and an assessment of evidentiary value in research on the psychological consequences of scarcity. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 118(44).",NA,NA,"0.157341","r","0.003603726","r",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/a2e96/",NA,"2.0","openMKT16",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Consumer Research",NA,NA,NA,NA
"1229","OpenMKT17","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","parental decision making, family spending, economic recessions, evolutionary psychology","In times of greater economic scarcity, the preference for giving resources to girls (vs. boys) will be moderated by individual differences in risk aversion with greater differences between economic conditions in resource allocation to girls (vs boys) for participants with higher levels of trait risk aversion.",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45158.0",NA,NA,"0.1786519","0.08199041","198.0","573.0","Durante, K. M., Griskevicius, V., Redden, J. P., & Edward White, A. (2015). Spending on daughters versus sons in economic recessions. Journal of Consumer Research, 42(3), 435-457. Study 4","O’Donnell, M., Dev, A. S., Antonoplis, S., Baum, S. M., Benedetti, A. H., Brown, N. D., … & Nelson, L. D. (2021). Empirical audit and review and an assessment of evidentiary value in research on the psychological consequences of scarcity. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 118(44).",NA,NA,"0.1786519","r","0.08199041","r",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/a2e96/",NA,"2.0","openMKT17",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Consumer Research",NA,NA,NA,NA
"1230","OpenMKT18","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","scarcity, abundance, preference within a choice set, choices of the favorite, resource constraints, preference polarization","Perceiving four varieties of vegetables (carrots, broccoli, cauliflower, tomatoes) as relatively scarce will 1. increase relative preferences for individuals’ favorite of the four 2. Lead to individuals’ favorite vegetable being chosen more from a choice in which participants can select six pieces of vegetable.",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45158.0",NA,NA,"0.1378405","0.001836483","200.0","595.0","Zhu, M., & Ratner, R. K. (2015). Scarcity polarizes preferences: The impact on choice among multiple items in a product class. Journal of Marketing Research, 52(1), 13-26. Study 2","O’Donnell, M., Dev, A. S., Antonoplis, S., Baum, S. M., Benedetti, A. H., Brown, N. D., … & Nelson, L. D. (2021). Empirical audit and review and an assessment of evidentiary value in research on the psychological consequences of scarcity. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 118(44).",NA,NA,"0.1378405","r","0.001836483","r",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://osf.io/a2e96/",NA,"2.0","openMKT18",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Marketing Research",NA,NA,NA,NA
