"1233","datareplicada2","1.0","LK","Individual submissions","self-construal, choice, group size, joint consumption","This study examines the hypothesis laid out in the authors’ abstract: “interdependent consumers consistently make choices that balance self and others’ preferences, regardless of group size. In contrast, the choices of independent consumers differ depending on group size: for smaller groups, independents make choices that balance self and others’ preferences, while for larger groups, they make choices that more strongly reflect their own preferences.”",NA,"Kaiser, Leonard","45166.0",NA,NA,NA,"0.05","250.0","1305.0","Wu, E.C., Moore, S.G., & Fitzsimons, G.J. (2019). Wine for the Table: Self-Construal, Group Size, and Choice for Self and Others. Journal of Consumer Research. Study 3","Simmons, J. &. Nelson, L.D. (2020). [83] Data Replicada #2: Do Self-Construal and Group Size Influence How People Make Choices on Behalf of a Group? Data Colada. https://datacolada.org/83 Replication 2",NA,NA,NA,NA,"0.05","beta",NA,NA,NA,NA,"https://aspredicted.org/gc74h.pdf",NA,"0.0","2.0",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"t(239) = 2.20, p = .03",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"informative failure to replicate",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Journal of Consumer Research",NA,NA,NA,NA
